    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Learning Point}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    All nonzero digits are significant.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    All zeros between nonzero digits are significant.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Leading zeros (to the left of the first nonzero digit) are not significant.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Trailing zeros to the right of the decimal place are significant.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Zero appearing after non-zero digit. On the whole numbers
                    side may be significant or may not be significant figures.
                    It can be a place holder or a significant.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                How many significant figures are there in the following masses?
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>45.023</m> kg
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>120</m> kg
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>145.60</m> kg
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.0023</m> kg
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>45.023</m> kg
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            All nonzero digits are significant and zeros between them count as significant.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Thus <m>45.023</m> kg contains five significant digits.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>120</m> kg
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            All the zeros that are on the right of the last non-zero digit are significant if they come from a measurement.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Thus <m>120</m> kg contains three significant digits.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>145.60</m> kg
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            All the zeros that are on the right of the last non-zero digit, after the decimal point, are significant.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Thus <m>145.60</m> kg contains five significant digits.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.0023</m> kg
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Leading zeros are never significant
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Thus <m>0.0023</m> kg contains two significant digits.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Express each of the following numbers to the given number of significant figures in brackets:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>12891 \quad (3)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.02789 \quad (2)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>12891 \quad (3)</m> 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           The number <m>12891</m>  has five significant digits.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To round it off to three significant
                            figures, we consider the <alert>fourth significant digit</alert>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The fourth significant digit is <m>9</m>, which is <alert>greater than</alert>
                            <m>5</m>. Therefore, we add <m>1</m> to the third significant digit and replace
                            the fourth and fifth significant digits with zeros.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Thus, <m>12891</m> to three significant figures is <m>12900</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In this case, zeros serve as placeholders and not significant figures.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.02789 \quad (2)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           The number <m>0.02789</m> has four significant digits because the leading zeros are not significant digits. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To round it off to two significant digits,
                            we consider the <alert>third significant digit</alert>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The third significant digit is <m>8</m>, which is <alert>greater
                            than</alert> <m>5</m>. Therefore, we add <m>1</m> to the second significant digit and
                            we remove the remaining digits.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Thus, <m>0.02789</m> correct to <m>2</m> significant digit is <m>0.028</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
